        [
          "Staff Generated History"
        ],
        [
          "As a child you would sit with your dad in the market and look at the live stock. He taught you from a very young age what desireable things to look for in the daily deliveries, and how to barter with the teller. You negotiated your first purchase at the age of 10, bringing in two new families to work on the farm. You skipped along merrily, jerking a pregnant Negress along the dirt around, esctatic to show your father your first purchase. While you learned how to buy, you also learned how to treat them, as that woman died from you dragging her along several weeks later. You never let another slave die under your watch again. By the time you were 17 you were ready to take over the family plantation, while your father traveled deeper East to establish a second plantation. That was when William joined your business - while also a Negro, he had the know how and the literacy to walk by your side at market, and he pointed out things about the slaves you wouldn't have noticed otherwise. How to spot a sick slave before the slave itself even knew. Or if the slave would be good for house work instead of field work. Those slaves he would help you purchase though, he didn't turn them out to the field. He bathed them, cut their hair, taught them how to be like William himself; accountants, drivers, slaves of a more domestic kind. You worked in front, listening to what your clients wanted, and finding a slave that would suit their needs, sometimes driving picks into their eyes to keep the Negros docile. Your sire brought you fully into this business of match making slaves to their owners just in time for the war to take off, and word was sent of your family dying in the Boston massacre. You decided to give your business partner the go ahead to sell off the slaves, sell the property, and turn you. Within months after your parents were buried you began your trek into the world of darkness, and learning to deal in slaves of a different kind."
        ],
